# Evergreen Toolkit - Sample Crontab
#
# After running deploy.sh, a pre-filled version is generated at
# config/crontab.generated with your workspace path substituted.
# You can also customize this template manually.
#
# Usage: cp config/crontab.sample /tmp/my-crontab && nano /tmp/my-crontab && crontab /tmp/my-crontab
#
# IMPORTANT: This crontab uses wrapper scripts for reliable execution.
# Do NOT use 'source .venv/bin/activate' in cron - it doesn't work in cron's minimal environment.
# Use absolute Python paths instead. Sourcing `.memory_env` (simple exports) is fine.

# ============================================================
# ENVIRONMENT SETUP
# ============================================================
# Cron runs with minimal PATH - we must specify everything explicitly
#
# IMPORTANT: Set WORKSPACE below to your deployed workspace path.
# If you used deploy.sh, this is the --workspace path you specified.
# Cron does NOT expand ~ or $HOME in command paths.
PATH=/usr/local/bin:/usr/bin:/bin:/usr/local/sbin:/usr/sbin
SHELL=/bin/bash
WORKSPACE=/path/to/openclaw-workspace

# ============================================================
# TIMEZONE: Adjust all times for your local timezone
# ============================================================
# Example times below assume America/Chicago (CST/CDT)
# Check your timezone: timedatectl
# Set if needed: sudo timedatectl set-timezone America/New_York

# ============================================================
# MEMORY & BACKUP (Before Evergreens) - CRITICAL ORDER!
# ============================================================
# IMPORTANT: True Recall MUST run before Jarvis backup.
# - True Recall reads Redis buffer, extracts gems, does NOT clear Redis
# - Jarvis backup reads Redis, backs up to Qdrant, THEN clears Redis
# - If Jarvis runs first, True Recall has nothing to process!
#
# What happens if the order is wrong? Jarvis clears the Redis buffer after
# backing up. If it runs before True Recall, the curated gem extraction
# gets an empty buffer and produces no gems for that day. Raw backups in
# Qdrant are still preserved, but the high-salience extraction is lost.
#
# Each user gets their own Redis key (mem:<user1>, mem:<user2>, etc.)
# Jarvis clears only the specific user's key after that user's backup
# succeeds, so <user1>'s 3:00 AM job won't affect <user2>'s buffer at 3:05 AM.
# Jobs are spaced 5 minutes apart to avoid resource contention.
# ============================================================

# True Recall curation: Extract high-salience memories (2:30 AM)
# Does NOT clear Redis - Jarvis handles that
#
# TWO-TIER STORAGE (default): curate_memories.py defaults to the
# `true_recall` collection, while cron_backup.py (Jarvis) defaults to
# `<agent>-memories`. This keeps curated gems separate from raw backups.
# Override with QDRANT_COLLECTION env var if needed.
30 2 * * * cd $WORKSPACE && source $WORKSPACE/.memory_env && $WORKSPACE/.venv/bin/python3 $WORKSPACE/memory/scripts/curate_memories.py --user-id <user1> >> $WORKSPACE/logs/true-recall.log 2>&1
35 2 * * * cd $WORKSPACE && source $WORKSPACE/.memory_env && $WORKSPACE/.venv/bin/python3 $WORKSPACE/memory/scripts/curate_memories.py --user-id <user2> >> $WORKSPACE/logs/true-recall.log 2>&1

# Jarvis Memory backup: Redis → Qdrant (3:00 AM)
# Clears Redis buffer after successful backup
0 3 * * * cd $WORKSPACE && source $WORKSPACE/.memory_env && $WORKSPACE/.venv/bin/python3 $WORKSPACE/memory/scripts/cron_backup.py --user-id <user1> >> $WORKSPACE/logs/memory-backup.log 2>&1
5 3 * * * cd $WORKSPACE && source $WORKSPACE/.memory_env && $WORKSPACE/.venv/bin/python3 $WORKSPACE/memory/scripts/cron_backup.py --user-id <user2> >> $WORKSPACE/logs/memory-backup.log 2>&1

# Session capture: New transcript messages → Redis (every 5 minutes)
# Tracks byte offsets to only process new additions since last run.
# This is separate from cron_backup.py — it feeds data INTO Redis,
# while cron_backup.py moves data OUT of Redis to Qdrant.
# NOTE: Multi-user entries run at the same interval but are safe to overlap.
# If you experience file lock contention on shared JSONL transcript files,
# stagger entries (e.g., */5 offset by 1 minute: 1,6,11,... for user2).
*/5 * * * * cd $WORKSPACE && source $WORKSPACE/.memory_env && $WORKSPACE/.venv/bin/python3 $WORKSPACE/memory/scripts/cron_capture.py --user-id <user1> >> $WORKSPACE/logs/session-capture.log 2>&1
*/5 * * * * cd $WORKSPACE && source $WORKSPACE/.memory_env && $WORKSPACE/.venv/bin/python3 $WORKSPACE/memory/scripts/cron_capture.py --user-id <user2> >> $WORKSPACE/logs/session-capture.log 2>&1
# Staggered alternative (if you experience file lock contention):
# */5 * * * * cd $WORKSPACE && source $WORKSPACE/.memory_env && $WORKSPACE/.venv/bin/python3 $WORKSPACE/memory/scripts/cron_capture.py --user-id <user1> >> $WORKSPACE/logs/session-capture.log 2>&1
# 1,6,11,16,21,26,31,36,41,46,51,56 * * * * cd $WORKSPACE && source $WORKSPACE/.memory_env && $WORKSPACE/.venv/bin/python3 $WORKSPACE/memory/scripts/cron_capture.py --user-id <user2> >> $WORKSPACE/logs/session-capture.log 2>&1

# Full system backup (3:30 AM) - Replace with your actual backup script
# Runs after memory backup completes
30 3 * * * /path/to/your/backup-script.sh >> $WORKSPACE/logs/backup.log 2>&1

# ============================================================
# PARA PROMOTION (Weekly) - True Recall gems → PARA durable knowledge
# ============================================================
# Runs weekly (Sunday 2:00 AM, before True Recall) to promote high-value
# gems to PARA items.json. Uses tiered contradiction resolution:
#   Tier 1: Auto-supersede (timestamps, versions)
#   Tier 2: Auto-supersede + log (preferences, opinions)
#   Tier 3: Queue for conversational review (relationships, identity)
#
# Each user gets their own promotion run.
# --hours 168 = process last 7 days of gems since last promotion.
0 2 * * 0 cd $WORKSPACE && source $WORKSPACE/.memory_env && $WORKSPACE/.venv/bin/python3 $WORKSPACE/memory/scripts/promote_to_para.py --user-id <user1> --hours 168 >> $WORKSPACE/logs/para-promotion.log 2>&1
5 2 * * 0 cd $WORKSPACE && source $WORKSPACE/.memory_env && $WORKSPACE/.venv/bin/python3 $WORKSPACE/memory/scripts/promote_to_para.py --user-id <user2> --hours 168 >> $WORKSPACE/logs/para-promotion.log 2>&1

# ============================================================
# EVERGREENS - AI-Orchestrated Mode (Recommended)
# ============================================================
# The AI runner spawns a full AI agent session via `openclaw agent`.
# The agent reads context, runs real commands, analyses findings,
# and writes substantive reports — performing the cognitive work
# that scripted executors cannot do.
#
# Requirements:
# - OpenClaw installed and on PATH
# - OpenClaw gateway running (auto-falls back to embedded mode if not)
#
# Each runs at its own time with 30-minute intervals.
# Default timeout: 1500s (25 min). Override below for research-heavy evergreens.
#
# NOTE: upstream-architecture and household-memory typically run ~30 min,
# which exceeds the default 25-min timeout. The entries below override
# to EVERGREEN_TIMEOUT=2400 (40 min) for those two. You can also set
# globally in the crontab environment:
#   EVERGREEN_TIMEOUT=2400
#
# MODEL OVERRIDE (optional):
# By default, evergreens use your system's default model. To route
# evergreens to a more capable model (e.g., for technical accuracy):
#
#   1. Create a named agent:
#      openclaw agents add evergreen --model "provider/model" --workspace "/path/to/workspace"
#
#   2. Set EVERGREEN_AGENT in your crontab environment:
#      EVERGREEN_AGENT=evergreen
#
#   Or override per-evergreen inline:
#      0 4 * * * EVERGREEN_AGENT=heavy-model /path/to/scripts/evergreen-ai-runner.sh upstream-architecture
#
#   Leave EVERGREEN_AGENT unset to use the system default model.
#
# FAILURE NOTIFICATIONS (optional):
# Set EVERGREEN_NOTIFY_TARGET to receive alerts when a run fails and
# files are rolled back. The target depends on your messaging channel
# (e.g., phone number for WhatsApp/SMS, channel ID for Slack/Discord).
# Configure your channel in openclaw.json first, then set the target:
#
#   EVERGREEN_NOTIFY_TARGET=<your-phone-number>
#
# Leave unset to skip notifications (failures are still logged).
#
# CROSS-EVERGREEN BRIEFING:
# Each successful run appends a summary to evergreens/daily-briefing-YYYYMMDD.md.
# Later evergreens read this file for cross-cutting context from earlier runs.
# This happens automatically — no configuration needed.
# ============================================================

# upstream-architecture: 4:00 AM (~30 min runtime — 40-min timeout, overrides default 25 min)
0 4 * * * EVERGREEN_TIMEOUT=2400 $WORKSPACE/scripts/evergreen-ai-runner.sh upstream-architecture

# system-health: 4:30 AM
30 4 * * * $WORKSPACE/scripts/evergreen-ai-runner.sh system-health

# prompt-injection: 5:00 AM
0 5 * * * $WORKSPACE/scripts/evergreen-ai-runner.sh prompt-injection

# household-memory: 5:30 AM (~30 min runtime — 40-min timeout, overrides default 25 min)
30 5 * * * EVERGREEN_TIMEOUT=2400 $WORKSPACE/scripts/evergreen-ai-runner.sh household-memory

# Final Check: 6:00 AM (verify all ran, send notification)
# Uses --force flag to always send status (success or failure)
# Configure your notification in openclaw.json (WhatsApp, Telegram, etc.)
0 6 * * * $WORKSPACE/scripts/final-check-wrapper.sh

# ============================================================
# WEEKLY DEEP-ANALYSIS CYCLE (Optional — Opt-In)
# ============================================================
# A once-per-week meta-cycle that performs heavier, LLM-powered analysis
# across all evergreens: semantic learning compaction, cross-evergreen
# synthesis, PARA candidate extraction, Next Steps triage, trend projection.
#
# Daily cycles work fine without this. The weekly cycle produces enrichment
# files (weekly-synthesis-YYYYMMDD.md) that daily cycles read if available.
#
# Prerequisites: Same as daily AI runner (openclaw on PATH, gateway running).
# Budget: ~60-90 min single LLM session, runs once per week.
#
# The script runs the shell-side keyword synthesis first (no LLM), then
# spawns an AI agent for deeper semantic analysis. If the LLM step fails,
# the shell-side output remains as fallback.

# Weekly deep analysis: Sunday 6:30 AM (after daily cycles and final-check)
30 6 * * 0 $WORKSPACE/scripts/evergreen-weekly-cycle.sh

# ============================================================
# OPTIONAL: Shell-Side Weekly Synthesis Only (No LLM)
# ============================================================
# If you don't want the full LLM-powered weekly cycle but still want
# cross-evergreen keyword overlap detection, run the shell-side synthesis
# standalone. This is already called by the full weekly cycle script above,
# so don't enable both.
#
# 30 6 * * 0 cd $WORKSPACE && $WORKSPACE/.venv/bin/python3 $WORKSPACE/scripts/weekly-synthesis.py --days 7 >> $WORKSPACE/logs/weekly-synthesis.log 2>&1

# ============================================================
# OPTIONAL: Additional Monitoring
# ============================================================

# Morning diagnostic: Manual check with status output (7:00 AM)
# Useful for debugging - outputs JSON status to log
0 7 * * * cd $WORKSPACE && $WORKSPACE/.venv/bin/python3 $WORKSPACE/scripts/evergreen-final-check.py --status >> $WORKSPACE/logs/evergreen-diagnostic.log 2>&1

# Weekly log cleanup: remove log files older than 30 days (Sunday midnight)
0 0 * * 0 find $WORKSPACE/logs/ -name "*.log" -mtime +30 -delete

# ============================================================
# ROTATION SCHEDULE (OPTIONAL)
# ============================================================
# By default every evergreen runs once a day (see above).
# If you prefer to rotate them across different days to reduce
# nightly load, uncomment and adapt the examples below.
#
# Example: run each evergreen on a specific weekday (0=Sun … 6=Sat)
# 0 4 * * 1 $WORKSPACE/scripts/evergreen-ai-runner.sh upstream-architecture  # Monday
# 0 4 * * 2 $WORKSPACE/scripts/evergreen-ai-runner.sh system-health           # Tuesday
# 0 4 * * 3 $WORKSPACE/scripts/evergreen-ai-runner.sh prompt-injection        # Wednesday
# 0 4 * * 4 $WORKSPACE/scripts/evergreen-ai-runner.sh household-memory        # Thursday

# ============================================================
# SETUP INSTRUCTIONS
# ============================================================
# 
# 1. Copy this file:
#    cp config/crontab.sample /tmp/my-crontab
#
# 2. Edit with your paths and user IDs:
#    nano /tmp/my-crontab
#    - Set WORKSPACE variable at the top to your deployed workspace path
#      (e.g., /home/yourname/.openclaw/workspace — NOT the cloned repo)
#    - Replace <user1>, <user2> with your actual user IDs
#    - Adjust times for your timezone
#
# 3. Install the crontab:
#    crontab /tmp/my-crontab
#
# 4. Verify installation:
#    crontab -l
#
# 5. Check logs after first run:
#    tail -f $WORKSPACE/logs/evergreen-system-health-$(date +%Y%m%d).log
#    tail -f $WORKSPACE/logs/evergreen-final-check.log
#
# 6. Test manually before relying on cron:
#    cd $WORKSPACE
#    ./scripts/evergreen-ai-runner.sh system-health
#
# ============================================================
# TROUBLESHOOTING
# ============================================================
# 
# If evergreens don't run:
# - Check cron daemon: systemctl status cron (or crond on some systems)
# - Check cron logs: grep CRON /var/log/syslog | tail -20
# - Verify scripts are executable: chmod +x scripts/*.sh
# - Check gateway health: openclaw health
# - Test AI runner manually: ./scripts/evergreen-ai-runner.sh system-health
#
# If notifications don't arrive:
# - Verify OpenClaw channel is configured: openclaw channels list
# - Test notification manually: openclaw message send --target <your-phone-number> --message "test"
# - Check final check log: tail logs/evergreen-final-check.log
#
